Limit of Panic
Copenhagen – We often hear that the world as we know it will meet its end in a way, usually through ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been with us since the Club of Rome’s seminal work, "The Limits to Growth," was released over forty years ago.
But time is not generous.
The 1972 "Limits to Growth" warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was looming.
But instead of genuine shortages or production collapse, we saw financial panics.
Human ingenuity continues to provide more than enough resources to satisfy human consumption.
Yet the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we are stuck in a trend of chasing misleading solutions to minor issues while ignoring major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism waned, the Vietnam War became a disaster, societies fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
With Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" igniting fears of pollution and sparking the modern environmentalist movement, Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
In the first Earth Day of 1970, there was widespread pessimism.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate because too many people consume too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children at significantly lower levels of poverty for social stability.
This view still resonates, despite being fundamentally wrong.
For instance, the authors of The Limits to Growth predicted that the world would deplete aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
But, while commodity prices have recently rebounded, they overall remain at about one-third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dental amalgams, and thermometers, reducing mercury consumption by 98% by 2000 and prices by 90%.
Broader speaking, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have exceeded demand, thanks to new discoveries of reserves and more economical refining techniques.
Similarly, oil and gas were expected to run out in 1990 and 1992, respectively; yet both reserves are now above 1970 levels despite our consumption having risen substantially.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled America's potential natural gas resource base and cut prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will rise 14-fold this century, with developing countries rising 24-fold.
The Limits to Growth went wrong because the authors ignored the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began to slow in the 1960s.
Food supplies did not collapse (there are 1.5 billion hectares of cultivated land in use, plus an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
Nutrition deficiencies have been halved, dropping from 35% of the world population to 16%.
We have also managed pollution.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where we had no air pollution and were all happy farmers, and in the future, smokestacks from home heating would make it impossible to breathe. Reality is the opposite.
By 1900, the global population was 1.5 billion, and nearly three million people — equivalent to one person in every 500 — died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, the death toll has fallen to one per 2,000 people.
While pollution-related deaths are still higher than those from malaria, the death rate is falling rather than rising.
尽管如此，《增长的极限》所培养的观念仍在左右公众和精英的思维。
Take recycling, for example, which is typically a feel-good gesture that is expensive and ineffective for the environment.
比如，纸张通常来自可持续森林而不是热带雨林。
The programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies driven by fear of population overgrowth, such as China's family planning and India's forced sterilizations, have led to self-destructive outcomes.
此外，尽管杀虫剂和其他污染物曾被认为会杀死一半的人类，良好的杀虫剂管制让每年美国因杀虫剂死亡的人数仅有20例，并且杀虫剂的使用创造了更廉价、更充足的粮食供给。
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — the movement inspired by insecticide panic — would impose an extra annual cost of $100 billion on the US.
Agricultural efficiency would drop by 16%, requiring an additional 65 million hectares of farmland to maintain current output — half the area of modern-day California.
Rising prices will lead to reduced fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including thousands of additional cancer deaths annually).
Being fixated on worst-case scenarios prevents us from addressing the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, claiming 15 million lives annually — a quarter of all deaths — from easily treatable diseases.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world to reduce the number of poor by nearly one billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The four decades since the publication of The Limits to Growth show that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring over $100 trillion in benefits annually by the end of the century, far exceeding the cautionary "feel-good" policies fueled by fear.
This requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
